  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most countries, including China. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds appear legal by disguising the true origin of the funds. This is typically done through a series of transactions and financial maneuvers.\n\nIn China, the Anti-Money Laundering Law, which was enacted in 2007 and amended in subsequent years, explicitly prohibits money laundering activities. The law establishes a comprehensive framework for preventing and combating money laundering, including measures for reporting suspicious transactions, conducting customer due diligence, and establishing financial intelligence units.\n\nViolations of anti-money laundering laws can result in severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment. Chinese authorities are committed to enforcing these laws to maintain the integrity of the financial system and to combat organized crime, terrorism financing, and other illicit activities.",
